Quick "Suspicious Everything" One-Liners (run as root)
Bash# All cron-like things
(for u in $(cut -f1 -d: /etc/passwd); do echo "Crontab $u"; crontab -u $u -l 2>/dev/null; done; cat /etc/crontab; ls -la /etc/cron.* /var/spool/cron/) 2>/dev/null

# All systemd custom units
find /etc/systemd /usr/lib/systemd /run/systemd -type f -name '*.service' -o -name '*.timer' -exec grep -H Exec {} + 2>/dev/null

# Shell profiles + SSH keys + .ssh dirs
(for d in /root /home/*; do echo "$d"; [ -d "$d/.ssh" ] && cat "$d/.ssh/authorized_keys" 2>/dev/null; cat "$d"/.{bash,zsh}{rc,_profile,_login} 2>/dev/null; done) 2>/dev/null

# udev + PAM + LD_PRELOAD
(find /etc/udev/rules.d/ /lib/udev/rules.d/ -type f -exec grep -H RUN {} +; grep -rEi 'pam_exec|pam_script' /etc/pam.d/; grep -rEi 'LD_PRELOAD|LD_LIBRARY_PATH' /etc/ /home/*/.bashrc* 2>/dev/null) 2>/dev/null

# Strange SUID + world-writable
(find / -type f -perm -4000 -o -perm -2000 -o -perm -0002 2>/dev/null | grep -vE '^/(usr|bin|sbin|lib)') 2>/dev/null
Additional Tips

Baseline first — Run these on a clean system to know what is normal.
Auditd / Sysmon for Linux — Enable them to log file writes to /etc/crontab, /etc/systemd/, .ssh/authorized_keys, etc.
File integrity monitoring — Use AIDE, Tripwire, or OSSEC to watch critical directories.
Reboot test — After cleaning, reboot and check ps auxf, netstat -tuln, ss -tuln, last, w for surprises.
Rootkits — Run rkhunter --check, chkrootkit, or lynis audit system.
